<TITLE> Tamim reveals plan for direct power to consumers </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 16 (bdnews24.com)  The government has moved to allow direct transmission of power, generated in the private sector, to consumers, said M Tamim, a special assistant to the chief adviser, Wednesday. Prof Tamim revealed the new plan by the government at a seminar in the city, where a top businessman said that businesses would not take up new ventures if "energy security" was not ensured. The government has also started a market study on liquid natural gas (LNG) to face the gas crisis, Tamim told the seminar on "Better business through eco and energy efficiency" at The Westin Dhaka. Tamim, who is in charge of the power, energy and mineral resources ministry, said the power transmission line would be opened to the private sector so that it could generate and consume its own electricity. He said that 80 percent of the energy policy recommendations had not been implemented. "Our policies should be integrated. Implementation is related to leadership. Leadership is based on knowledge and understanding," he added. "Now we have better scope to save energy by efficiency. Our immediate focus should be exploration and conservation. We should go for solar thermal energy. We are going to make mandatory solar heating system for all buildings. We would like to include this system in our building code," Tamim said. "To increase efficiency we have to change our habit. Time has come to revisit our def
